Author: cevr <seeve.c@gmail.com>
Date:   Wed Jun 17 17:47:50 2026 -0400

    feat(forms)(submissions): Submissions.persist service (persist-only) + tests

    The durable half of the submission pipeline (CONTEXT ┬зSubmission, settled #8;
    registration-launch Branch 7.2). `Submissions.persist(form, decoded)` encodes a
    decoded form to its definition-derived `Submission` envelope and `Storage.put`s it
    at `submissions/<form>/<id>.json`, returning the stored record тАФ persistence ONLY,
    no mailer.

      - small-interface-deep-implementation: the service exposes exactly ONE op,
        `persist`. Splitting persist (this module) from notify (the action's terminal
        step, Branch 7.3) is what makes "a notify failure cannot lose the record" a
        real, testable property: persist returns the stored Submission BEFORE any
        notification runs, so a downstream mailer failure still leaves the object.
      - derive-dont-sync: the payload codec is submissionSchema(definition) тАФ the same
        schema derived from the form's FormDefinition the generic decoder validates
        against тАФ read via Content.getForm (Branch 5.3). The id (newListItemId) and
        bucket key (submissionKey) are derived too, never hand-typed.
      - make-impossible-states-unrepresentable: form is the closed FormId, submittedAt
        a branded real-calendar IsoDate, id a branded ListItemId. A decoded form always
        re-encodes; a structurally-wrong payload dies rather than half-writing.

    Adds submissionKey(form, id) to the page/form registry alongside the other derived
    key templates. Tests pin the durable write, the on-bucket round-trip through the
    derived schema, distinct-ids-distinct-keys, persist-decoupled-from-notify, and the
    registration payload tracking the FormDefinition type (the registrar's read
    contract). Gate green. 7.3 (persist-then-notify wiring) follows.

